-- Japan, Philippines, Singapore, South Korea: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-09-27T22:47:05Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-27/japan-philippines-singapore-south-korea-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in Tokyo. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m.  Masamitsu Sakurai , head of the Japan
Association of Corporate Executives, will hold a media briefing
at 1:30 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Shoko Chukin Bank will release at 2 p.m. in Tokyo its
report on confidence among small businesses for September.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.99 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 84.30 per dollar at 7:40 a.m. in Tokyo.  Philippines: The National Statistics Office will announce
July import data and the trade balance.  The government will auction 8.5 billion pesos ($194
million) of 25-year bonds.  The yield on the 6.125 percent debt due September 2020 was
6.16 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 44.013.  Singapore: The government is scheduled to sell S$1.6
billion ($1.2 billion) of five-year bonds today.  The yield on the 3.25 percent debt due September 2020 was
2.01 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3212.  South Korea: The nation’s consumer confidence fell to the
lowest level in 14 months amid concern that the nation’s
economic recovery will slow.  The sentiment index declined for a second straight month to
109 in September from 110 in August, the Bank of Korea said in
an e-mailed statement in Seoul today. The index’s recent peak
was a seven-year high of 117 in October. A number exceeding 100
indicates optimists outnumber pessimists.  The yield on the 3.75 percent note due June 2013 was 3.39
percent. The won was at 1,148.20 per dollar.  Taiwan: The government is scheduled to sell NT$30 billion
($956 million) of 182-day bills today.  The yield on the 1.125 percent bond due September 2020 was
1.21 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The Taiwan
dollar was at NT$31.47.  To contact the reporter on this story:
